<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>How to Use This Calculator</h2>

  <h3>Workplace Pension tab</h3>
  <p>Enter your <strong>current age</strong> and <strong>retirement age</strong> (default 67). Add your <strong>annual salary</strong>, <strong>employee contribution</strong> (e.g. 5%) and <strong>employer contribution</strong> (e.g. 3%). If you already have a pension pot, enter its current value. Finally, set your expected <strong>annual investment return</strong> — the calculator projects your total pot at retirement and your estimated annual income using the 4% safe withdrawal rule.</p>

  <h3>State Pension tab</h3>
  <p>Enter your <strong>National Insurance qualifying years</strong> (you need 35 for the full State Pension). The calculator shows your weekly and annual State Pension entitlement based on the current full rate of £230.25 per week.</p>

  <h3>Share your result</h3>
  <p>Every input is encoded in the URL. Click <strong>Share</strong>, send the link — they'll see your exact numbers. No re-entering, no screenshots.</p>
</section>

<!-- ── FORMULA ── -->
<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>The Formula</h2>
  <p>Workplace pension projections use the <strong>future value of a growing investment with regular contributions</strong>. The State Pension is a proportion of the full rate based on qualifying years.</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    FV = PV(1+r)<sup>n</sup> + PMT &times; [(1+r)<sup>n</sup> &minus; 1] / r
  </div>
  <p>Where <strong>FV</strong> is the future value of your pension pot, <strong>PV</strong> is the current pot, <strong>r</strong> is the annual return rate, <strong>n</strong> is years to retirement, and <strong>PMT</strong> is total annual contributions (employee + employer).</p>

  <h3>State Pension</h3>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Weekly State Pension = (Qualifying Years / 35) &times; £230.25
  </div>
  <p>You need a minimum of 10 qualifying years to receive any State Pension. The maximum is 35 years for the full amount.</p>

  <h3>Annual retirement income</h3>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Annual Income = Pension Pot &times; 4% (safe withdrawal rule)
  </div>
  <p>The <strong>4% rule</strong> is a widely used guideline suggesting you can withdraw 4% of your pot each year for a sustainable retirement income lasting roughly 30 years.</p>
</section>

